text: On Sunday, July 12th around 11am I and a car ahead of me had turned left on to GA 128 east bound just before the Flint River between Roberta and Reynolds Ga.  This is the same 2 lane state hwy where an 11 year old girl had recently been hit by a tractor trailer beside her mailbox, with a steady police presence for speeders since.  Nonetheless, a Trantham Farms semi pulling a tanker trailer came up behind us as we were still accelerating from our turn on to the road, getting less than a car length from my rear bumper even after I reach 63-65mph on the 55mph 2 lane road.  I finally pass the car ahead of me but as I leave Roberta on US 341 north, where it's 4 lanes in town with 45mph zone become 2 lanes outside city limits, the same truck suddenly comes flying up on my right just as the last of any pavement for it's lane ends, pushing me into the southbound lane.  This was after the previous 1/4 miles of 4 lanes had several signs indicating the trucks lane ends, and even after vehicles parked on the right shoulder with hazards on should have had the truck over to give clearence in the first place.  I had to slam on my brakes as there was no way to maintain my speed and my lane without the truck hitting me.  All of this occurred within a 10 minutes of turning on to GA 128 back near the Flint.  Now behind the truck, it places between 68 and 72 mph of 2 lane road including GA 42 to Forsyth, a curvy, hilly 16 miles with no passing lanes and only a few short passing zones. It's all on dashcam.  At no time did I brake check, race beside, or otherwise taunt the driver as they drove in a manner that proves they do not belong behind the wheel of these huge vehicles. I will be contacting the Forsyth destination at the feed processing plant.

text:
Barry Blueberry Farm

Let’s start with the good. Nice fields with plenty of bushes for picking. Prices are decent and the experience was fun.

Now let’s get to the bad.

Upon arrival we were asked how many people were going to be picking. We had a group of 7 & all wanted to pick berries. The man behind the counter stated the conversation by questioning how many buckets we wanted & then proceeded to question if we were all really going to pick. He then said that he “saw a lot of Hollow legs”.  (Insinuating that we might be stealing berries.  We were shocked but didn’t really think that he was saying that.

We explained that we all wanted to pick and took our buckets and started collecting our berries.

Overall the experience was good because we made the best of it.

Would we come back ? Possibly not.  Sad because we thought it would be a recurring activity when in Alabama.

text: I knew nothing of this company until I’d received a gift for Teacher’s Appreciation week purchased from 1818 Farms. I was sold immediately on their product! I’ve since ordered from them several times. I buy their whipped shea butter mostly - it’s creamy without being greasy and a little goes a long way! I’ve also purchased their products for gifts - needless to say, my mom and grandmother are now hooked! While this review/comment is based on my experiences with this company on a whole, my most recent experience, specifically, is what encouraged me to form a review for the public. I recently placed an order for two of their gift boxes and a couple of single items. The order contained Mother’s Day gifts for my mom and grandmother. The order was received, processed and delivered PROMPTLY - like within two business days (I didn’t pay extra for expedited shipping). I received a text alert when the product was delivered - around noon, yday. It was quite warm outside and I still had hours before I’d get home from work. I was a bit worried about the product sitting in the heat/sun. As soon as I got home, I unpacked the box. The way it was packed so carefully and with consideration was a plus, BUT I also noticed that there was a Koolit refrigerant pack placed in the bottom of my carefully packed order...packed in anticipation of a warm day and no one being home to receive the package once it arrived. This may seem like a small thing. This may seem like “common” sense and good business practices, but as someone who does a LOT of online shopping, I can assure you that many businesses don’t put even a fraction of thought and consideration into packing their product for delivery. 1818 Farms has a lifetime customer!
